    {"course_id": 2, "title": "Night Driving & Riding for EVs", "content": "## Night Driving & Riding for EVs\n\n### Visibility Safety\nDrivers and riders must:\n- Use headlights properly (low beam in town, high beam on dark roads)\n- Wear reflective gear\n- Reduce speed at night (10-15 km/h slower)\n- Keep windshields and visors clean\n\n### Common Night Hazards\n- Poor visibility (especially on unlit roads)\n- Pedestrians without reflective clothing\n- Animals crossing roads\n- Unmarked vehicles without lights\n- EV silence means pedestrians may not hear you coming\n\n### EV-Specific Night Tips\n- Ensure headlights are LED (many EVs have bright LEDs)\n- Don't blind oncoming traffic with high beams\n- Use fog lights in poor conditions\n- Keep charging port area clean to avoid debris in dark", "order": 6},
    {"course_id": 2, "title": "Wet Weather EV Operations", "content": "## Wet Weather EV Operations\n\n### Safety Guidelines\n\n**During Rain:**\n- Reduce speed (wet roads = longer stopping distance)\n- Increase following distance (4+ seconds)\n- Avoid sudden braking\n- Avoid flooded roads\n\n### Hydroplaning Prevention\nHydroplaning occurs when tyres lose road contact due to water.\n\n**Prevention:**\n- Maintain proper tyre pressure\n- Ensure adequate tread depth\n- Reduce speed in standing water\n- Avoid sudden steering or braking\n\n**If hydroplaning:**\n- Don't brake suddenly\n- Ease off accelerator\n- Steer straight until tyres regain contact\n\n### EV-Specific Wet Weather Notes\n- EVs are well-sealed, safe in rain\n- Avoid deep puddles (may damage underbody connectors)\n- Regenerative braking reduces skid risk\n- After flood exposure, have battery inspected", "order": 7},
